This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:44 AM; Case called for Hearing. Defendant Dashianna S Edmonds in court.  Attorney Jeffrey W. Jensen Jr. in court for Dashianna S Edmonds.  Prosecuting attorney Charles Patrick Hoffmann in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty. Jensen provides an update; he just received additional discovery and just needs a little more time to review everything and decide how to proceed.  Atty. State has no objection to the request for Zoom appearance.  Court will adjourn for further proceedings.  Court will approve the defendant to appear by Zoom for the next court date.
Hearing scheduled for December 8, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

Hearing scheduled for November 2, 2022 at 10:30 am.
